message: Here are some behind the scenes photos from the inauguration today. One of the photos includes three former U.S. presidents, including President Carter, President Clinton and President Bush. The second photo includes some of the justices of the U.S. Supreme Court.
Great opportunity to meet with President Trump and Vice President Pence today in Philadelphia at Senate GOP meetings.

Our next Supreme Court justice will make decisions that impact our country for generations. That’s why it’s important to confirm someone who will apply the law, not legislate from the bench.    Judge Gorsuch is a mainstream nominee with an extensive and impressive judicial career. He has a record of fiercely defending religious freedoms. His experience with issues affecting the Rocky Mountain West will make him unique among his fellow justices. I look forward to a thorough confirmation process.

Today, the Senate delivered a major victory for coal country. The Senate and House both passed a resolution of disapproval, brought under the Congressional Review Act, that repeals the Obama administration's anti-coal stream rule.   This flawed stream rule ignored the input of state regulators, including those in Wyoming, and put thousands of jobs in jeopardy. I look forward to working with Congress and the Trump administration to repeal more midnight regulations like this one.
Congratulations to Wilson’s Mike Hoeft and the Aspen Pines Water and Sewer District for winning gold in the National Rural Water Association (NRWA)'s 2017 Great American Water Taste Test.
Thanks to the Wyoming Legislature for letting me visit with you today--it's an event I always look forward to.
Great to hear from so many people across #Wyoming tonight on our tele-town hall. Mike Enzi and I always enjoy hearing your thoughts and ideas.
Great visiting with Lander's Susan Fessler, gold medalist in cycling at the 2014 Special Olympics USA Games.

It was wonderful to be at the Casper airport to help welcome home six Wyoming National Guard members who are returning home from Afghanistan.   It was great to see the service members again. I had the opportunity to visit with them in Afghanistan this past Thanksgiving. Welcome home to all of the members of the B Battery, 2nd Battalion, 300th Field Artillery from across Wyoming. I'm so glad they're home safe and reunited with their loved ones.

Bobbi and I join all of Wyoming in mourning the loss of Wyoming legend John Wold.   As a former U.S. Congressman, entrepreneur and philanthropist, John did it all. He truly exemplified our Wyoming values and Western spirit. Even after retiring from public office, he never stopped working for the people of Wyoming. John and his wife Jane were famous for their kind hearts and their generosity to organizations across our great state. As a professional geologist, John’s contributions to the mining industry revolutionized the way our nation extracts minerals today.   I will miss John’s friendship and his love for all things Wyoming. Bobbi and I send our heartfelt condolences to his children Peter, Jack, and Priscilla, and the entire Wold family.

Interns play a vital role in both my D.C. and state offices. The deadline for our summer program is fast approaching. My staff will be in Laramie at the UW Career and Internship Fair today to talk about all that our internships entail, but you can also find more information on my website.
Thanks to the students at Casper's Park Elementary for welcoming me to their school today. It was great to visit with so many future Wyoming leaders.

It was great to be at the White House today when President Trump signed the executive order to revise the misguided Waters of the United States (WOTUS) rule. The WOTUS rule, issued under the Obama administration, placed backyard ponds, large puddles, and plowed farm fields under Washington’s control. Small businesses, farmers, and ranchers would be hurt by this excessive rule, and there was bipartisan opposition to it in Congress.  We need to clarify the distinction between state and federal waters. It is vital we do so in a responsible way that respects state and local authority while using common sense. I will continue to work with the Trump administration as it addresses WOTUS.

The president gave an address filled with the same spirit of optimism that I hear from people all around Wyoming. Tonight, he spoke to all Americans. In particular, I commend his emphasis on creating jobs and giving Americans relief from the failed Obamacare law.   It’s encouraging to see that President Trump is already moving to keep his promises to the American people. I look forward to working with the White House on ways to expand opportunities for people in Wyoming and across the country.
Here is why yesterday's executive order on #WOTUS is so significant for farmers, ranchers and small businesses across the country.
Here’s a behind the scenes look at my meeting with Supreme Court nominee Judge Gorsuch today. More photos and video to follow.

I just had a great visit with Neil Gorsuch. Neil Gorsuch, in my opinion, is the right person for America and certainly from a Wyoming standpoint. His mom was born in Casper. The family built the Wolf Hotel in Saratoga before Wyoming was even a state.  But the thing I like best about Judge Gorsuch is that he believes and understands fully that the Constitution is a legal document, not a living document. It was built for rigidity, not flexibility. He is one justice who will make sure that he applies the law and doesn’t write the law. I look forward to supporting his nomination.

Great news for Wyoming today. A federal court ruled to uphold the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service’s 2012 decision to remove the gray wolf in Wyoming from the endangered species list. The state of Wyoming has put together a working plan to protect the state’s wolf population. I am pleased that the court agrees that the wolf has recovered enough to be removed from the endangered species list. As a result of this ruling, the state’s wolves will be under the control of Wyoming, not Washington.
I had a great time at the Rawlins Friends of the NRA banquet this weekend. #Wyoming #SecondAmendment

#Wyoming is well represented at the 2017 United States Senate Youth Program by Devils Tower's Grace Anderson and Powell's Nicole Sanders. Both Grace and Nicole will receive scholarships. Senator Mike Enzi and I had the opportunity to congratulate them on this wonderful achievement. #USSYP
Enjoyed showing the Peterson family from Cheyenne around the United States Capitol on this snowy day.
This is why i support Judge Neil Gorsuch.

Great to be at the White House for the signing ceremony today of a resolution overturning BLM's Planning 2.0 rule. Here is Sublette County Commissioner Joel Bousman giving his cowboy hat to President Trump.

Today, President Trump signed a resolution to roll back another harmful Obama administration midnight rule. The misguided BLM Planning 2.0 rule would have taken authority away from local land managers who have the most knowledge and experience overseeing resources in their own districts. Local management plans must include key input from county commissioners, sportsmen, local businesses and those who interact daily with these landscapes.   I want to thank Representative Liz Cheney and Senator Lisa Murkowski for taking the lead on this resolution in the House and Senate. Now that this rule is overturned, we can work together on a new policy that makes the planning process more efficient and improves input at the local level.

Today, President Trump signed a resolution to roll back another harmful Obama administration midnight rule. The misguided BLM Planning 2.0 rule would have taken authority away from local land managers who have the most knowledge and experience overseeing resources in their own districts. Local management plans must include key input from county commissioners, sportsmen, local businesses and those who interact daily with these landscapes.   I want to thank Representative Liz Cheney and Senator Lisa Murkowski for taking the lead on this resolution in the House and Senate. Now that this rule is overturned, we can work together on a new policy that makes the planning process more efficient and improves input at the local level.

It was an honor to be at the Environmental Protection Agency today to watch President Trump sign the energy independence executive order. This executive order is welcome news for energy-producing states like Wyoming. The Obama administration’s punishing regulations have done far more harm to our economy than good for the environment. I applaud President Trump for taking action on behalf of America’s families and energy workers. Federal agencies will now have the opportunity to identify ways to improve the environment without hurting job growth.
It was great to visit with the Lemley family from Cheyenne today. I last saw Jonathan in 2014 when he was deployed with the Wyoming National Guard in Qatar.
It was fun to join Albin Elementary School's virtual field trip to Washington, D.C. today. Always great to visit with #Wyoming students.

Today, the Senate confirmed one of the most highly qualified judges in the country to sit on the U.S. Supreme Court. During his career on the bench, Judge Gorsuch has been a model of integrity, intelligence and independence. He will also bring a unique Rocky Mountain perspective to the court. Judge Gorsuch is a fitting replacement for the seat vacated by the late Justice Scalia, and I’m proud to have supported his confirmation.   Here is a video of my meeting with Judge Gorsuch back in March. I presented him with a photo of the The Historic Wolf Hotel and Restaurant in Saratoga. Judge Gorsuch’s family built the Wolf Hotel before Wyoming was even a state.
It was great to see such a big crowd at the Wyoming Association of Rural Water Systems Spring Training Conference in Casper today.
Had a great time speaking with students from Sheridan High School and Jackson Hole High School who are visiting the nation's capital today.

Today, the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia released its final order concerning the gray wolf in Wyoming. The order upholds the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service’s 2012 decision to delist the gray wolf in Wyoming from the endangered species list. This puts the management of the wolf where it should have been all along, under the control of Wyoming, not Washington.
Enjoyed visiting with students from Casper, Guernsey, Riverton, Wheatland and Worland this morning during #WyomingWednesday.
It was great to visit with so many people at the Bridger Valley Health Fair and Rural Electric meeting today. Thanks to the #FFA team for serving up breakfast.

Today, the United States and China announced the end of a 13-year ban on U.S. beef imports to China. This is a huge step forward for American producers who have been shut out of the market for more than a decade. After recently traveling to China to meet with Chinese Premier Li on this issue, I’m pleased he worked with the Trump administration to make this a reality. Ranchers in Wyoming will now have access to a larger market to sell our high-quality American beef.
Thank you to United States Capitol Police for their bravery today and every day. Our thoughts are with them, Congressman Steve Scalise and the other victims of this attack.
Students from all over Wyoming were in DC this week. They represented Casper, Jackson, Lander, Laramie, Torrington & Wheatland. #WYinDC
Congratulations to Casper's Jerry Knight on winning the #JeffersonAward for his unwavering commitment to community service. #WYinDC

After seven years of disruption and disappointment, it’s urgent that we act now to replace Obamacare with a new law that finally puts patients first and begins to stabilize insurance markets that teeter on the verge of collapse.  What we are proposing today steers health care sharply away from federal mandates, higher taxes and government control. Instead, our draft bill puts the focus on affordability, access to care with more choices, and safeguards Medicaid for the most vulnerable and needy.  The bill is not perfect, and because of budget rules it doesn’t include every prescription I would have liked. What I do know is that our path is a vast improvement over Obamacare and will finally start to build a health care system that works for many more Americans.  Over the next week, we will be working to improve on this draft with broad input from health care providers, patients, and every member of the U.S. Senate.
Looking forward to sitting down with Brit Hume on Fox News Sunday tomorrow morning to discuss the draft Senate health care bill. In Wyoming, you can watch it at 8 am MT on your local FOX station.
Sat down with Brit Hume on Fox News Sunday to discuss how the draft Senate health care bill is a fundamental shift away from Obamacare.
Bobbi and I want to wish everyone a happy #IndependenceDay.
Great to be in Cody yesterday and today to celebrate Independence Day. Thanks to Longmire stars Robert Taylor and Adam Bartley for serving as the Grand Marshals of the parade.
Our bipartisan HELP for Wildlife Act promotes conservation based on sound science and provides needed protections for Wyoming’s sportsmen. It also solidifies the delisting of gray wolves.

Today, Department of Interior Secretary Ryan Zinke signed Secretarial Order 3354 to help streamline oil and gas permitting. For years, energy production has been bogged down by permitting delays in BLM offices across the West. If applications aren’t being approved, our economy suffers and we lose out on job opportunities in our local communities. I’m encouraged that today’s secretarial order will get the ball rolling on making necessary reforms to help BLM field offices address the growing backlog. It’s important that BLM has a system in place that allows them to effectively and efficiently process these permits.
It was great to talk about health care this morning with Maria Bartiromo LIVE from beautiful Casper, Wyoming on FOX News "Sunday Morning Futures.”

We have a great deal of admiration, appreciation, and respect for the people who are being hit by these natural disasters across the country. Thanks to all of the first responders, rescue workers and volunteers who have committed their time and effort to help.
We’ll #neverforget those who lost their lives on September 11, 2001.

Congratulations to Newcastle’s Tracy Ragland on being named the Wyoming principal of the year. Thanks for all you do to help our students succeed.

In March, I held a Senate Environment and Public Works Committee hearing on preventing destructive floods. Washakie County Commissioner Terry Wolf testified at the hearing about the need to address ice-jam flooding in Worland. I’m pleased to report that after that hearing, the Army Corps of Engineers inspected the site and local crews were able to successfully remove a sandbar in the Big Horn River that was contributing to this flooding. The community of Worland is now safer with this project completed.
What an incredible Border War win for Wyoming football. The bronze boot stays in Laramie. #GoWyo
Another outstanding Cowboys Against Cancer benefit in Rock Springs this weekend thanks to the incredible work of Margaret Parry, Al Harris and all of the wonderful volunteers.

Congratulations to Torrington’s Lois Van Mark and Douglas’ Chad Rupe on being appointed to leadership roles within the U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA). Lois was appointed to be the USDA Farm Service Agency state executive director in Wyoming. Rupe was appointed to serve as Wyoming’s USDA state director for Rural Development. Both Lois and Chad have strong ties and experience in Wyoming’s rural communities. I know they will continue to represent our state well in their roles at the USDA.
We want tax reform that allows you to keep more of what you earn, and a system that’s fair for all Americans.

Americans should be alarmed that the Committee on Foreign Investment in the United States (CFIUS) approved the sale of Uranium One to the Russian government, despite evidence that Russian nuclear energy officials engaged in corrupt conduct. The investigation of what happened and who knew about it is ongoing. Today, I joined Senator John Cornyn (R-TX) and others in introducing bipartisan legislation to address this issue and to safeguard our national security. Now, we can begin to actually reform the approval process and add much-needed transparency and accountability. The Foreign Investment Risk Review Modernization Act (FIRRMA) prevents the sale of critical U.S. technology to our foreign adversaries. It also requires CFIUS to disclose to Congress evidence of criminal conduct by foreign parties to a deal. This will add critical safeguards to prevent risky foreign takeovers of American businesses.
We’re going to pass tax reform, tax cuts and tax relief for the American people.

Bobbi and I wish you and your family a happy Thanksgiving.

Sharing Thanksgiving with Wyoming troops overseas is always an honor. There are 106 members of the Wyoming Air National Guard’s 187th Airlift Squadron serving in Kuwait. They are a long way from home and it was nice to bring a little bit of Wyoming to them for the holidays. So much of our gratitude goes to these brave men and women who are doing an incredible job keeping America and our allies safe. As we take time to count our blessings this holiday season, please remember the sacrifice that our service members and their families make every day.
In addition to sharing Thanksgiving dinner, the Wyoming Air National Guard’s 187th Airlift Squadron also gave me a tour of their workstations, aircraft and briefed me on their mission.
Thanks to President Trump for attending the Senate Republican Policy Committee policy discussion today. We’re one step closer to getting tax reform done for the American people.
Senate Republicans had a productive meeting with President Trump today about tax reform. We’re committed to lowering tax rates and letting Americans keep more of their hard-earned money.

Late last night, the Senate passed the John P. Smith Act (S. 302). Tribal roads are some of the most dangerous and deadly in the country. With the Senate passage of this bill, we’re now one step closer to fixing these neglected roads and ultimately saving lives.   This legislation couldn’t have a better namesake. Wyoming’s John Smith was a life-long advocate for transportation safety who earned respect across the country—including at the White House. John brought tribal, state and local leaders together to improve safety on the Wind River Reservation. We couldn’t have passed this bill without John’s support and expert testimony before the Senate in years past. I look forward to the House passing this bill soon and adding to John’s already impressive legacy of improving lives across Indian Country.  http://bit.ly/2AtZHI8
We have a once-in-a-generation opportunity to cut taxes in a way that will actually help American families.

Local Casper volunteers did an incredible job of placing a wreath on every grave at the Oregon Trail State Veterans Cemetery today. Wreaths Across America is a great way to honor those who have served.

Congress is set to pass a historic tax reform bill that will repeal one of the most unfair parts of Obamacare—the individual mandate tax. This means Americans will no longer pay a penalty if they decide that overpriced Obamacare insurance is not right for them.

Today, Congress passed a once-in-a-generation tax relief bill that will allow people in Wyoming and across the country to keep more of their hard-earned money. Americans will now have a simpler, fairer tax code that will grow our economy, increase wages, and create jobs.   In addition to lowering the rates Americans have to pay, the bill doubles the child tax credit, allows more medical-expense deductions and keeps tax relief for retirement savings, charitable giving and mortgage interest. It nearly doubles the standard deduction to let folks keep more of their paychecks and save time when they file their taxes.   It also repeals one of the most unfair parts of Obamacare – the individual mandate tax. This means Americans will no longer pay a penalty if they decide that overpriced Obamacare insurance is not right for them.   I have always believed the best way for Washington to give Americans the most value for their money is to let them keep it at home. This bill does that, while making American businesses more competitive and unleashing the full potential of our economy.
